loitation. In Social Exchange, Brian J. Burke provides a deep ethnographic investigation of this activism and its effects. This story draws us into the cultural and material effects of capitalism and narco-violence, while also helping us understand what new radical imaginations look like and how people bring them to life. The result is an intimate glimpse of urban life in Latin America, as well as a broader analysis of non-capitalist or post-capitalist possibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aBarterxEconomic aspectszColombia. 0aBarterxSocial aspectszColombia. 0aSocial exchange. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCultural activism, Medellín, Colombia, Medellín, Colombia, barter markets, alternative currencies, economic systems, South American economy, Latin American Economies, alternative economies, globalization, hegemony, economic change, bartering, barterers, barter system, grassroots activism, narco-violence, ethnography, Colombian cultural movements, capitalist culture, social movement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978829657?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978829657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978829657/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK